summary.seg: This richly ornamented Gospel lectionary manuscript was probably copied in the last years of the 10th century, and is written in an unusual hybrid form of majuscule script.

During the 9th century Greek majuscule script was supplanted by the more compact minuscule form for most purposes, being retained largely for headings and annotations, but for centuries some manuscripts continued to be produced in majuscule. This was most common in lectionaries, perhaps partly because the larger, more distinct and initially more familiar letter-forms were easier to read at a glance for those chanting the text in church, and partly because the use of a more ancient and traditional form had connotations of greater dignity which were appropriate to the most revered of scriptural texts, and to a type of manuscript whose ceremonial purpose meant that they were often particularly ornate and costly productions.

The earliest clearly defined style of Greek majuscule bookhand is known as biblical majuscule, with letters of broad and even width, originally without serifs. The second widespread style, flourishing later but in simultaneous use, is known as ogival majuscule, which features prominent serifs and narrower proportions, especially in the case of the rounded letters epsilon, theta, omicron and sigma. During the early minuscule era biblical majuscule largely dropped out of use, and such majuscule production as continued generally employed either an ogival style or a new hybrid style known as liturgical or Constantinopolitan majuscule, crystallising in the 10th century, which followed the broad forms of the round letters from the biblical style and its smooth, oval omega, while other letters accorded with the ogival type. In this manuscript a different and less consistent synthesis is found, with regular use of both the wide and narrow forms of the round letters. Forms of upsilon and chi as well as omega follow the biblical style, other letters the ogival.

support.material: Parchment (FHHF), of medium thickness and quality.

supportDesc.foliation: The manuscript is foliated with the numbers [i-iii] + 1-199 + [iv-vi], in pencil, in Arabic numerals, recto, upper right and recto, lower right.

collation.p: The manuscript consists of 28 quires, of which one is a binion, two are quinia and the rest are quaternia. Another three quires have been lost after Quire 19, as the signature on Quire 21 indicates that there were originally three more quires in the manuscript up to this point, and this is the only previous lacuna in the text long enough to accommodate them. Further quires have been lost after 23, but it is not possible to determine how many, due to the lack of complete quire signatures thereafter and the uncertain quantity of text in a menologion.

collation.signatures: There are quire signatures in Greek numerals, in brown ink, on the first folio of each quire, in pencil, recto, upper right, probably original to the production of the manuscript. They survive in whole on Quire 21 (κδʹ), in part on Quires 20 (κ), 22 and 26 (λ), and traces of them on Quires 9, 13 and 25.

There are modern quire signatures in Arabic numerals, in pencil, on the first folio of each quire, recto, lower right (1-27), and in Roman numerals n the last folio of each quire, verso, lower left (I-XXVII).

supportDesc.condition: There have been losses from the edges of various folios, which have been repaired with parchment patches (e.g. ff. 1-3, 191-199. Similar repairs have been made to holes within ff. 1-2. There is damage from oak-gall corrosion, which on occasion has produced holes in folios (e.g. ff. 1-2, 176). There is water staining, which has contributed to severe discoloration of ff. 1r-2r, and areas of dirt.

layoutDesc.layout:
Two columns of 20 lines. 215 165
Pricking survives in the lower margin, but much has been lost to cropping. Ruled in hardpoint, system Leroy 1, type Leroy C-K 46C2c. Text stands on the lines.

handNote.p: The text was copied in brown ink in script combining elements of upright ogival majuscule and biblical majuscule scripts: both the narrow and wide forms of epsilon, theta, omicron and sigma are in regular use, while the forms of upsilon, chi andomega are typical of biblical majuscule, while other letters follow the ogival style. When appearing at the end of a line, omega often appears in a vertically squashed form.
The horizontal stroke for nu is in use and there are some superscript word endings at the end of lines. Breathings and accents are in use.

Punctuation used includes the middle and upper points, middle comma, question mark and full stop. Middle and upper points are occasionally marked in red ink, and on other occasions are very often accompanied by a cross in red ink.
Headings and other rubric were written partly in the style of the main text but in smaller letters, in brown ink, and partly in a display majuscule script in red ink and gilded.

physDesc.musicNotation: The text has been provided with ekphonetic notation in red ink.

decoDesc.decoNote: The beginning of the text on f. 1r is preceded by an arched headpiece in red, blue, green and white paint and gold, topped by two peacocks. The beginnings of other sections are preceded by rectangular headpieces in red, blue, green and white paint and gold (ff. 101v, 188v, 191r, 192r and 197r-197v).
Each lection begins with an ornamented major initial, outlined in gold with red, blue, green and white paint infill.
The beginning of various sections and headings are marked by minor initials in gold.
Lection headings and rubrics were written in red ink and gilded.

additions.p: As part of the original production of the manuscript, lection notes have been included in the margins.
There is a note of the number of folios on the right pastedown, apparently dated 15 August 1908 and initialed H.A.C.

binding.p: Full leather binding by Zaehnsdorf, 1903, as indicated by a gold-tooled note inside the left board, with parchment pastedowns. Both boards have decorative gold tooling on the inner face and blind tooling on the outer faces and edges. There is decorative blind tooling on the spine, along with the gold-tooled text Evangelistarium Greek uncials seculum IX. The edges have been painted red.

physDesc.accMat: There are separate sewn parchment endleaves, belonging to the present binding. There is a bookplate indicating ownership by Frank McClean on the left pastedown.

history.origin: The manuscript was probably copied in the late 10th century, as suggested by the style of script.
history.provenance: Purchased by the astronomer and collector Frank McClean (1837-1904) McClean, F. (Frank), 1837-1904 from the bookseller Bernard Quaritch (1819-1899) Quaritch, Bernard, 1819-1899 .
history.acquisition: Bequeathed to the Fitzwilliam Museum by McClean, together with the rest of his collection, in 1904.

availability.p: Visitors to the Fitzwilliam Museum who wish to consult Collection material are required to apply to the Museum in advance of their visit. For information on eligibility and admission procedures see: Fitzwilliam Museum: Study Room.
